article.description:
Swin Cash kept up her offensive tear as
the Detroit Shock continued to build the best record in the WNBA.
article.headline: Cash helps Shock win fifth straight game
article.linkText: Cash, Shock rout Sun, clinch playoff spot
article.story:
UNCASVILLE, Conn. (AP) -- Swin Cash kept up her offensive tear as
the Detroit Shock continued to build the best record in the WNBA.

Cash scored 17 of her 20 points in the first half to lead the
Shock to a 78-61 victory over the Connecticut Sun on Tuesday night.
Detroit (19-6) has won five straight games and Cash, whose college
career included two national championships with Connecticut, is
averaging 20 points over that stretch.

"We wanted to come out here and be very aggressive and set the
tone for the rest of the game," Cash said. "We are fighting for
the Eastern Conference and we go out and play hard for 40
minutes."

Center Ruth Riley and Kedra Holland-Corn each added 13 points
and rookie forward Cheryl Ford grabbed 12 rebounds for Detroit,
which tightened its grip on first place in the East with the best
record in the league. The Sun are 0-4 against the Shock this
season.

"They are the best team in the league," Sun coach Mike
Thibault said. "They have embarrassed us. They came with a great
energy and are playing with a lot of confidence."

The Shock led by as many as 21 points and were up 47-28 at
halftime, scoring easily and often in transition. The 19-point
halftime deficit was the largest for Connecticut (14-13) this
season.

Katie Douglas led the Sun with 14 points and six rebounds, while
Nykesha Sales and Taj McWilliams-Franklin each scored 11 points.

Deanna Nolan, who had 10 points for Detroit, pulled down a
career-high nine rebounds.

The Sun struggled from the field and couldn't keep pace with
Detroit's speedy transition game and inside power.

Detroit's dominant inside trio of Cash, Riley and Ford clogged
up the middle, giving Connecticut little room to work. Detroit
outscored Connecticut 50-30 in the paint and finished with 38-27
edge on the boards.

"Our patience and execution were outstanding and our defense
was again great stuff," Detroit coach Bill Laimbeer said. "We are
only two games up on Los Angeles (18-8) right now and that's how we
are viewing the world. We want to see if we can secure the best
record."

Connecticut found the going just as futile early from the
outside, hitting 1-of-12 from behind the arc in the first half.

The Shock extended their lead to 23 points in the second half.
The Sun mounted a small rally on three straight 3-pointers by
Douglas, but would get no closer than 13 points.

"They knew what they wanted to do to stop us on defense," Sun
guard Shannon Johnson said. "We did not meet their level of
competition."
